In this sentence, semi-presidential republics refer to a type of republic where both a president and a prime minister coexist and share power.

Parliamentary republics refer to a form of government where the executive branch (led by a prime minister) is accountable to the legislative branch (parliament) and is dependent on its confidence to remain in power. Examples of parliamentary republics include India, Germany, and Ireland.
